{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17476370","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17476370"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:45:57+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:45:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13735"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17583753","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17583753"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:28:18+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:28:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13735"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13735","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13735"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.31,0.02,0.46,0.03,0.18]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6354"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49121"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6354","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6354"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13735"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34156"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"41"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"2467"},{"type":"tags","id":"2602"},{"type":"tags","id":"2756"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"7567"},{"type":"tags","id":"8629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11806"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42917"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44169"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49121","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/49121"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA neonate is born at term via normal vaginal delivery. Apgar scores are eight and nine at one and five minutes respectively. On routine newborn examination, femoral pulses are difficult to palpate compared to brachial pulses. His four limb blood pressures show a gradient of 25 mmHg between the upper and lower limbs. Echocardiography confirms a discrete coarctation of the aorta distal to the left subclavian artery.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following embryological structures is implicated in the development of this boy\u0027s condition?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Truncus arteriosus","Ductus venosus","Ductus arteriosus","Foramen ovale","Ligamentum arteriosum"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ECoarctation of the aorta is a congenital narrowing of the aortic arch, typically just distal to the origin of the left subclavian artery. It results from abnormal development of the \u003Cstrong\u003Eductus arteriosus\u003C/strong\u003E and left 4th aortic arch during the 5th to 7th week of gestation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe ductus arteriosus is a normal fetal structure that connects the proximal descending aorta to the pulmonary artery, allowing the majority of blood from the right ventricle to bypass the lungs. After birth, functional closure of the ductus arteriosus occurs within 12-24 hours. Anatomic closure occurs within two to three weeks, leaving behind the \u003Cstrong\u003Eligamentum arteriosum\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAbnormal narrowing of the aortic arch in the region of the ductus arteriosus leads to the development of coarctation. The exact embryological mechanisms are not fully understood, but may involve abnormal intimal thickening, smooth muscle cell migration, or ductal tissue extending into the aortic wall.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eforamen ovale\u003C/strong\u003E is an opening between the right and left atria that allows oxygenated blood from the placenta to bypass the lungs in utero. Abnormalities of the foramen ovale are associated with atrial septal defects, not coarctation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Etruncus arteriosus\u003C/strong\u003E is a primitive vascular structure that gives rise to the ascending aorta and pulmonary trunk. Abnormal development here leads to persistent truncus arteriosus or transposition of the great arteries.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eductus venosus\u003C/strong\u003E is a fetal shunt that allows oxygenated blood from the umbilical vein to bypass the liver. It is not involved in the embryological development of coarctation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EClinically, coarctation of the aorta presents with differential blood pressure and pulse strength between the upper and lower limbs, as seen in this neonate. Management typically involves surgical repair or balloon angioplasty, depending on the severity and anatomy of the coarctation. Early diagnosis and treatment are crucial to prevent complications such as left ventricular hypertrophy, heart failure, and systemic hypertension. Long-term follow-up is necessary as there is a risk of re-coarctation and development of hypertension later in life.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Coarctation of the aorta is a congenital narrowing of the aortic arch, typically just distal to the left subclavian artery.","Coarctation results from abnormal development of the left 4th aortic arch during the 5th to 7th week of gestation.","The ductus arteriosus connects the pulmonary artery to the proximal descending aorta, allowing blood to bypass the lungs in utero."],"references":["Yokoyama U, Ichikawa Y, Minamisawa S, Ishikawa Y. Pathology and molecular mechanisms of coarctation of the aorta and its association with the ductus arteriosus. J Physiol Sci. 2017 Mar;67(2):259-270. Available at: https://doi.org/10.1007/s12576-016-0512-x"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34156"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13735"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34156","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/34156"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-07-23T16:54:14+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-05T20:57:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6354"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49121"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"41","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/41"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc80","name":"Anatomy","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"head